of
his
living
esteemed
him
highly.
It
was
only
with
young,
handsome,
fashionable,
and
stylish
ladies
he
felt
a
little
shy.
Being
himself
a
plain
man
plain
in
aspect,
plain
in
manners,
plain
in
speech
he
seemed
to
fear
their
dash,
elegance,
and
airs.
But
Miss
Helstone
had
neither
dash
nor
airs,
and
her
native
elegance
was
of
